`docs/` is the project's own documentation/governance layer, not source code, but it's authoritative over how the rest of the repo should be read and edited: it tells an engineer which architectural era they're in (pivoted, hook-based, post-broker), what's actually built versus planned, and why past designs were rejected. Anyone about to touch `ctx-context`, `ctx-cage`, `ctx-verify`, or the `.context/` tree should read here first — code comments and even other `intent.md` files defer to this directory for rationale.

The six files split cleanly by temporal role and must be read in the right order for a given question. `STATUS.md` is the live snapshot — trust its "Done/Open" split over any other file's impression of current state, including SPEC.md's body prose. `SPEC.md` is sealed except for its rev4 amendment paragraph, which supersedes large chunks of its own older body text (access protocol, summarization trigger, file-format prose) without deleting them — read the amendment before the section it amends. `DECISIONS.md` is the append-only rationale ledger explaining *why* SPEC and STATUS look the way they do; it cross-links via `[[ADR-NNN]]` and is where corrections-of-corrections live (e.g. ADR-032 walking back ADR-031). `SANDBOX.md` and (implicitly) parts of SPEC's old broker section are explicitly retired designs kept only as historical record — do not implement against them. `UNIMPLEMENTED.md` is the roadmap/debt tracker, and it explicitly says its own completion claims can silently drift out of sync with the crates it describes (a known coupling hazard, not yet enforced by tooling). `DYLINT_RULES.md` is the one purely forward-looking file — none of its nine rules exist yet, though rule 1's line-count check and rule 4's cycle check have partial mechanical equivalents already living in `scripts/`.

The load-bearing invariant across the set: SPEC.md's rollup/leaf line-budget numbers must stay numerically identical to `prompts/summarizer-rollup.md`, and the sandbox/cage architecture described consistently across STATUS, DECISIONS, and the retired SANDBOX.md must agree that enforcement is hook-based now, with cage as safety-only — any file here still describing broker/UDS enforcement as current is stale by definition.

No `intent.md` exists in this directory to check divergence against.